5459/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_BUS_MODE */
5460/*
5461 * RIB (RW)
5462 *
5463 * Rebuild INCRx Burst
5464 * When this bit is set high and the AHB master gets an EBT (Retry, Split, or Losing bus grant), the AHB master interface rebuilds the pending beats of any burst transfer initiated with INCRx. The AHB master interface rebuilds the beats with a combination of specified bursts with INCRx and SINGLE. By default, the AHB master interface rebuilds pending beats of an EBT with an unspecified (INCR) burst.
5465 */
5466#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_MASK (0x80000000UL)
5467#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_SHIFT (31U)
5468#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_MASK)
5469#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RIB_SHIFT)
5470
5471/*
5472 * PRWG (RW)
5473 *
5474 * Channel Priority
5475 * Weights This field sets the priority weights for Channel 0 during the round-robin arbitration between the DMA channels for the system bus.
5476 * - 00: The priority weight is 1.
5477 * - 01: The priority weight is 2.
5478 * - 10: The priority weight is 3.
5479 * - 11: The priority weight is 4. This field is present in all DWC_gmac configurations except GMAC-AXI when you select the AV feature. Otherwise, this field is reserved and read-only (RO).
5480 */
5481#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_MASK (0x30000000UL)
5482#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_SHIFT (28U)
5483#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_MASK)
5484#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PRWG_SHIFT)
5485
5486/*
5487 * TXPR (RW)
5488 *
5489 * Transmit Priority
5490 * When set, this bit indicates that the transmit DMA has higher priority than the receive DMA during arbitration for the system-side bus. In the GMAC-AXI configuration, this bit is reserved and read-only (RO).
5491 */
5492#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_MASK (0x8000000UL)
5493#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_SHIFT (27U)
5494#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_MASK)
5495#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_TXPR_SHIFT)
5496
5497/*
5498 * MB (RW)
5499 *
5500 * Mixed Burst
5501 * When this bit is set high and the FB bit is low, the AHB master interface starts all bursts of length more than 16 with INCR (undefined burst), whereas it reverts to fixed burst transfers (INCRx and SINGLE) for burst length of 16 and less.
5502 */
5503#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_MASK (0x4000000UL)
5504#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_SHIFT (26U)
5505#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_MASK)
5506#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_MB_SHIFT)
5507
5508/*
5509 * AAL (RW)
5510 *
5511 * Address-Aligned Beats
5512 * When this bit is set high and the FB bit is equal to 1, the AHB or AXI interface generates all bursts aligned to the start address LS bits. If the FB bit is equal to 0, the first burst (accessing the start address of data buffer) is not aligned, but subsequent bursts are aligned to the address.
5513 */
5514#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_MASK (0x2000000UL)
5515#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_SHIFT (25U)
5516#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_MASK)
5517#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_AAL_SHIFT)
5518
5519/*
5520 * PBLX8 (RW)
5521 *
5522 * PBLx8 Mode
5523 * When set high, this bit multiplies the programmed PBL value (Bits [22:17] and Bits[13:8]) eight times. Therefore, the DMA transfers the data in 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, and 256 beats depending on the PBL value.
5524 */
5525#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_MASK (0x1000000UL)
5526#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_SHIFT (24U)
5527#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_MASK)
5528#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBLX8_SHIFT)
5529
5530/*
5531 * USP (RW)
5532 *
5533 * Use Separate PBL
5534 * When set high, this bit configures the Rx DMA to use the value configured in Bits [22:17] as PBL. The PBL value in Bits [13:8] is applicable only to the Tx DMA operations. When reset to low, the PBL value in Bits [13:8] is applicable for both DMA engines.
5535 */
5536#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_MASK (0x800000UL)
5537#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_SHIFT (23U)
5538#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_MASK)
5539#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_USP_SHIFT)
5540
5541/*
5542 * RPBL (RW)
5543 *
5544 * Rx DMA PBL
5545 * This field indicates the maximum number of beats to be transferred in one Rx DMA transaction. This is the maximum value that is used in a single block Read or Write. The Rx DMA always attempts to burst as specified in the RPBL bit each time it starts a Burst transfer on the host bus. You can program RPBL with values of 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, and 32. Any other value results in undefined behavior. This field is valid and applicable only when USP is set high.
5546 */
5547#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_MASK (0x7E0000UL)
5548#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_SHIFT (17U)
5549#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_MASK)
5550#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_RPBL_SHIFT)
5551
5552/*
5553 * FB (RW)
5554 *
5555 * Fixed Burst
5556 * This bit controls whether the AHB or AXI master interface performs fixed burst transfers or not. When set, the AHB interface uses only SINGLE, INCR4, INCR8, or INCR16 during start of the normal burst transfers. When reset, the AHB or AXI interface uses SINGLE and INCR burst transfer operations.
5557 */
5558#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_MASK (0x10000UL)
5559#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_SHIFT (16U)
5560#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_MASK)
5561#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_FB_SHIFT)
5562
5563/*
5564 * PR (RW)
5565 *
5566 * Priority Ratio
5567 * These bits control the priority ratio in the weighted round-robin arbitration between the Rx DMA and Tx DMA. These bits are valid only when Bit 1 (DA) is reset. The priority ratio is Rx:Tx or Tx:Rx depending on whether Bit 27 (TXPR) is reset or set.
5568 * - 00: The Priority Ratio is 1:1.
5569 * - 01: The Priority Ratio is 2:1.
5570 * - 10: The Priority Ratio is 3:1.
5571 * - 11: The Priority Ratio is 4:1.
5572 */
5573#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_MASK (0xC000U)
5574#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_SHIFT (14U)
5575#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_MASK)
5576#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PR_SHIFT)
5577
5578/*
5579 * PBL (RW)
5580 *
5581 * Programmable Burst Length
5582 * These bits indicate the maximum number of beats to be transferred in one DMA transaction. This is the maximum value that is used in a single block Read or Write. The DMA always attempts to burst as specified in PBL each time it starts a Burst transfer on the host bus. PBL can be programmed with permissible values of 1, 2, 4, 8, 16, and 32. Any other value results in undefined behavior. When USP is set high, this PBL value is applicable only for Tx DMA transactions. If the number of beats to be transferred is more than 32, then perform the following steps: 1. Set the PBLx8 mode. 2. Set the PBL.
5583 */
5584#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_MASK (0x3F00U)
5585#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_SHIFT (8U)
5586#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_MASK)
5587#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_PBL_SHIFT)
5588
5589/*
5590 * ATDS (RW)
5591 *
5592 * Alternate Descriptor Size
5593 * When set, the size of the alternate descriptor (described in “Alternate or Enhanced Descriptors” on page 545) increases to 32 bytes (8 DWORDS). This is required when the Advanced Timestamp feature or the IPC Full Checksum Offload Engine (Type 2) is enabled in the receiver. The enhanced descriptor is not required if the Advanced Timestamp and IPC Full Checksum Offload Engine (Type 2) features are not enabled. In such case, you can use the 16 bytes descriptor to save 4 bytes of memory. This bit is present only when you select the Alternate Descriptor feature and any one of the following features during core configuration: - Advanced Timestamp feature - IPC Full Checksum Offload Engine (Type 2) feature Otherwise, this bit is reserved and is read-only. When reset, the descriptor size reverts back to 4 DWORDs (16 bytes).
5594 */
5595#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_MASK (0x80U)
5596#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_SHIFT (7U)
5597#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_MASK)
5598#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_ATDS_SHIFT)
5599
5600/*
5601 * DSL (RW)
5602 *
5603 * Descriptor Skip Length
5604 * This bit specifies the number of Word, Dword, or Lword (depending on the 32-bit, 64-bit, or 128-bit bus) to skip between two unchained descriptors. The address skipping starts from the end of current descriptor to the start of next descriptor. When the DSL value is equal to zero, the descriptor table is taken as contiguous by the DMA in Ring mode.
5605 */
5606#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_MASK (0x7CU)
5607#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_SHIFT (2U)
5608#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_MASK)
5609#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DSL_SHIFT)
5610
5611/*
5612 * DA (RW)
5613 *
5614 * DMA Arbitration Scheme
5615 * This bit specifies the arbitration scheme between the transmit and receive paths of Channel 0.
5616 * - 0: Weighted round-robin with Rx:Tx or Tx:Rx The priority between the paths is according to the priority specified in Bits [15:14] (PR) and priority weights specified in Bit 27 (TXPR).
5617 * - 1: Fixed priority The transmit path has priority over receive path when Bit 27 (TXPR) is set. Otherwise, receive path has priority over the transmit path.
5618 */
5619#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_MASK (0x2U)
5620#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_SHIFT (1U)
5621#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_MASK)
5622#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_DA_SHIFT)
5623
5624/*
5625 * SWR (RW)
5626 *
5627 * Software Reset
5628 * When this bit is set, the MAC DMA Controller resets the logic and all internal registers of the MAC. It is cleared automatically after the reset operation is complete in all of the DWC_gmac clock domains. Before reprogramming any register of the DWC_gmac, you should read a zero (0) value in this bit. Note: - The Software reset function is driven only by this bit. Bit 0 of Register 64 (Channel 1 Bus Mode Register) or Register 128 (Channel 2 Bus Mode Register) has no impact on the Software reset function. - The reset operation is completed only when all resets in all active clock domains are de-asserted. Therefore, it is essential that all PHY inputs clocks (applicable for the selected PHY interface) are present for the software reset completion. The time to complete the software reset operation depends on the frequency of the slowest active clock.
5629 */
5630#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_MASK (0x1U)
5631#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_SHIFT (0U)
5632#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_MASK)
5633#define ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_BUS_MODE_SWR_SHIFT)
5634
5635/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND */
5636/*
5637 * TPD (RW)
5638 *
5639 * Transmit Poll Demand
5640 * When these bits are written with any value, the DMA reads the current descriptor to which the Register 18 (Current Host Transmit Descriptor Register) is pointing. If that descriptor is not available (owned by the Host), the transmission returns to the Suspend state and Bit 2 (TU) of Register 5 (Status Register) is asserted. If the descriptor is available, the transmission resumes.
5641 */
5642#define ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_MASK (0xFFFFFFFFUL)
5643#define ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_SHIFT (0U)
5644#define ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_MASK)
5645#define ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_TX_POLL_DEMAND_TPD_SHIFT)
5646
5647/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_RX_POLL_DEMAND */
5648/*
5649 * RPD (RW)
5650 *
5651 * Receive Poll Demand
5652 * When these bits are written with any value, the DMA reads the current descriptor to which the Register 19 (Current Host Receive Descriptor Register) is pointing. If that descriptor is not available (owned by the Host), the reception returns to the Suspended state and Bit 7 (RU) of Register 5 (Status Register) is asserted. If the descriptor is available, the Rx DMA returns to the active state.
5653 */
5654#define ENET_DMA_RX_POLL_DEMAND_RPD_MASK (0xFFFFFFFFUL)
5655#define ENET_DMA_RX_POLL_DEMAND_RPD_SHIFT (0U)
5656#define ENET_DMA_RX_POLL_DEMAND_RPD_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_RX_POLL_DEMAND_RPD_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_RX_POLL_DEMAND_RPD_MASK)

5659/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_RX_DESC_LIST_ADDR */
5660/*
5661 * RDESLA (RW)
5662 *

5670

5673 * TDESLA (RW)

5682
5683/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_STATUS */
5684/*
5685 * GLPII (RW)
5686 *
5687 * GLPII: GMAC LPI Interrupt (for Channel 0)
5688 * This bit indicates an interrupt event in the LPI logic of the MAC. To reset this bit to 1'b0, the software must read the corresponding registers in the DWC_gmac to get the exact cause of the interrupt and clear its source. Note: GLPII status is given only in Channel 0 DMA register and is applicable only when the Energy Efficient Ethernet feature is enabled. Otherwise, this bit is reserved. When this bit is high, the interrupt signal from the MAC (sbd_intr_o) is high. -or- GTMSI: GMAC TMS Interrupt (for Channel 1 and Channel 2) This bit indicates an interrupt event in the traffic manager and scheduler logic of DWC_gmac. To reset this bit, the software must read the corresponding registers (Channel Status Register) to get the exact cause of the interrupt and clear its source. Note: GTMSI status is given only in Channel 1 and Channel 2 DMA register when the AV feature is enabled and corresponding additional transmit channels are present. Otherwise, this bit is reserved. When this bit is high, the interrupt signal from the MAC (sbd_intr_o) is high.
5689 */
5690#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_MASK (0x40000000UL)
5691#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_SHIFT (30U)
5692#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_MASK)
5693#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLPII_SHIFT)
5694
5695/*
5696 * TTI (RW)
5697 *
5698 * Timestamp Trigger Interrupt
5699 * This bit indicates an interrupt event in the Timestamp Generator block of the DWC_gmac. The software must read the corresponding registers in the DWC_gmac to get the exact cause of the interrupt and clear its source to reset this bit to 1'b0. When this bit is high, the interrupt signal from the DWC_gmac subsystem (sbd_intr_o) is high. This bit is applicable only when the IEEE 1588 Timestamp feature is enabled. Otherwise, this bit is reserved.
5700 */
5701#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_MASK (0x20000000UL)
5702#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_SHIFT (29U)
5703#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_MASK)
5704#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_TTI_SHIFT)
5705
5706/*
5707 * GPI (RW)
5708 *
5709 * GMAC PMT Interrupt
5710 * This bit indicates an interrupt event in the PMT module of the DWC_gmac. The software must read the PMT Control and Status Register in the MAC to get the exact cause of interrupt and clear its source to reset this bit to 1’b0. The interrupt signal from the DWC_gmac subsystem (sbd_intr_o) is high when this bit is high. This bit is applicable only when the Power Management feature is enabled. Otherwise, this bit is reserved. Note: The GPI and pmt_intr_o interrupts are generated in different clock domains.
5711 */
5712#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_MASK (0x10000000UL)
5713#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_SHIFT (28U)
5714#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_MASK)
5715#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_GPI_SHIFT)
5716
5717/*
5718 * GMI (RW)
5719 *
5720 * GMAC MMC Interrupt
5721 * This bit reflects an interrupt event in the MMC module of the DWC_gmac. The software must read the corresponding registers in the DWC_gmac to get the exact cause of the interrupt and clear the source of interrupt to make this bit as 1’b0. The interrupt signal from the DWC_gmac subsystem (sbd_intr_o) is high when this bit is high. This bit is applicable only when the MAC Management Counters (MMC) are enabled. Otherwise, this bit is reserved.
5722 */
5723#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_MASK (0x8000000UL)
5724#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_SHIFT (27U)
5725#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_MASK)
5726#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_GMI_SHIFT)
5727
5728/*
5729 * GLI (RW)
5730 *
5731 * GMAC Line Interface Interrupt
5732 * When set, this bit reflects any of the following interrupt events in the DWC_gmac interfaces (if present and enabled in your configuration): - PCS (TBI, RTBI, or SGMII): Link change or auto-negotiation complete event - SMII or RGMII: Link change event - General Purpose Input Status (GPIS): Any LL or LH event on the gpi_i input ports To identify the exact cause of the interrupt, the software must first read Bit 11 and Bits[2:0] of Register 14 (Interrupt Status Register) and then to clear the source of interrupt (which also clears the GLI interrupt), read any of the following corresponding registers: - PCS (TBI, RTBI, or SGMII): Register 49 (AN Status Register) - SMII or RGMII: Register 54 (SGMII/RGMII/SMII Control and Status Register) - General Purpose Input (GPI): Register 56 (General Purpose IO Register) The interrupt signal from the DWC_gmac subsystem (sbd_intr_o) is high when this bit is high.
5733 */
5734#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_MASK (0x4000000UL)
5735#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_SHIFT (26U)
5736#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_MASK)
5737#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_GLI_SHIFT)
5738
5739/*
5740 * EB (RW)
5741 *
5742 * Error Bits
5743 * This field indicates the type of error that caused a Bus Error, for example, error response on the AHB or AXI interface. This field is valid only when Bit 13 (FBI) is set. This field does not generate an interrupt.
5744 * - 0 0 0: Error during Rx DMA Write Data Transfer
5745 * - 0 1 1: Error during Tx DMA Read Data Transfer
5746 * - 1 0 0: Error during Rx DMA Descriptor Write Access
5747 * - 1 0 1: Error during Tx DMA Descriptor Write Access
5748 * - 1 1 0: Error during Rx DMA Descriptor Read Access
5749 * - 1 1 1: Error during Tx DMA Descriptor Read Access Note: 001 and 010 are reserved.
5750 */
5751#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_MASK (0x3800000UL)
5752#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_SHIFT (23U)
5753#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_MASK)
5754#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_EB_SHIFT)
5755
5756/*
5757 * TS (RW)
5758 *
5759 * Transmit Process State
5760 * This field indicates the Transmit DMA FSM state. This field does not generate an interrupt.
5761 * - 3’b000: Stopped; Reset or Stop Transmit Command issued
5762 * - 3’b001: Running; Fetching Transmit Transfer Descriptor
5763 * - 3’b010: Running; Waiting for status
5764 * - 3’b011: Running; Reading Data from host memory buffer and queuing it to transmit buffer (Tx FIFO)
5765 * - 3’b100: TIME_STAMP write state
5766 * - 3’b101: Reserved for future use
5767 * - 3’b110: Suspended; Transmit Descriptor Unavailable or Transmit Buffer Underflow
5768 * - 3’b111: Running; Closing Transmit Descriptor
5769 */
5770#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_MASK (0x700000UL)
5771#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_SHIFT (20U)
5772#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_MASK)
5773#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_TS_SHIFT)
5774
5775/*
5776 * RS (RW)
5777 *
5778 * Receive Process State
5779 * This field indicates the Receive DMA FSM state. This field does not generate an interrupt.
5780 * - 3’b000: Stopped: Reset or Stop Receive Command issued
5781 * - 3’b001: Running: Fetching Receive Transfer Descriptor
5782 * - 3’b010: Reserved for future use
5783 * - 3’b011: Running: Waiting for receive packet
5784 * - 3’b100: Suspended: Receive Descriptor Unavailable
5785 * - 3’b101: Running: Closing Receive Descriptor
5786 * - 3’b110: TIME_STAMP write state
5787 * - 3’b111: Running: Transferring the receive packet data from receive buffer to host memory
5788 */
5789#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_MASK (0xE0000UL)
5790#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_SHIFT (17U)
5791#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_MASK)
5792#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_RS_SHIFT)
5793
5794/*
5795 * NIS (RW)
5796 *
5797 * Normal Interrupt Summary
5798 * Normal Interrupt Summary bit value is the logical OR of the following bits when the corresponding interrupt bits are enabled in Register 7 (Interrupt Enable Register): - Register 5[0]: Transmit Interrupt - Register 5[2]: Transmit Buffer Unavailable - Register 5[6]: Receive Interrupt - Register 5[14]: Early Receive Interrupt Only unmasked bits (interrupts for which interrupt enable is set in Register 7) affect the Normal Interrupt Summary bit. This is a sticky bit and must be cleared (by writing 1 to this bit) each time a corresponding bit, which causes NIS to be set, is cleared.
5799 */
5800#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_MASK (0x10000UL)
5801#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_SHIFT (16U)
5802#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_MASK)
5803#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_NIS_SHIFT)
5804
5805/*
5806 * AIS (RW)
5807 *
5808 * Abnormal Interrupt Summary
5809 * Abnormal Interrupt Summary bit value is the logical OR of the following when the corresponding interrupt bits are enabled in Register 7 (Interrupt Enable Register): - Register 5[1]: Transmit Process Stopped - Register 5[3]: Transmit Jabber Timeout - Register 5[4]: Receive FIFO Overflow - Register 5[5]: Transmit Underflow - Register 5[7]: Receive Buffer Unavailable - Register 5[8]: Receive Process Stopped - Register 5[9]: Receive Watchdog Timeout - Register 5[10]: Early Transmit Interrupt - Register 5[13]: Fatal Bus Error Only unmasked bits affect the Abnormal Interrupt Summary bit. This is a sticky bit and must be cleared (by writing 1 to this bit) each time a corresponding bit, which causes AIS to be set, is cleared.
5810 */
5811#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_MASK (0x8000U)
5812#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_SHIFT (15U)
5813#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_MASK)
5814#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_AIS_SHIFT)
5815
5816/*
5817 * ERI (RW)
5818 *
5819 * Early Receive Interrupt
5820 * This bit indicates that the DMA filled the first data buffer of the packet. This bit is cleared when the software writes 1 to this bit or Bit 6 (RI) of this register is set (whichever occurs earlier).
5821 */
5822#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_MASK (0x4000U)
5823#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_SHIFT (14U)
5824#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_MASK)
5825#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_ERI_SHIFT)
5826
5827/*
5828 * FBI (RW)
5829 *
5830 * Fatal Bus Error Interrupt
5831 * This bit indicates that a bus error occurred, as described in Bits [25:23]. When this bit is set, the corresponding DMA engine disables all of its bus accesses.
5832 */
5833#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_MASK (0x2000U)
5834#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_SHIFT (13U)
5835#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_MASK)
5836#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_FBI_SHIFT)
5837
5838/*
5839 * ETI (RW)
5840 *
5841 * Early Transmit Interrupt
5842 * This bit indicates that the frame to be transmitted is fully transferred to the MTL Transmit FIFO.
5843 */
5844#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_MASK (0x400U)
5845#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_SHIFT (10U)
5846#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_MASK)
5847#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_ETI_SHIFT)
5848
5849/*
5850 * RWT (RW)
5851 *
5852 * Receive Watchdog Timeout
5853 * When set, this bit indicates that the Receive Watchdog Timer expired while receiving the current frame and the current frame is truncated after the watchdog timeout.
5854 */
5855#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_MASK (0x200U)
5856#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_SHIFT (9U)
5857#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_MASK)
5858#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_RWT_SHIFT)
5859
5860/*
5861 * RPS (RW)
5862 *
5863 * Receive Process Stopped
5864 * This bit is asserted when the Receive Process enters the Stopped state.
5865 */
5866#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_MASK (0x100U)
5867#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_SHIFT (8U)
5868#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_MASK)
5869#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_RPS_SHIFT)
5870
5871/*
5872 * RU (RW)
5873 *
5874 * Receive Buffer Unavailable
5875 * This bit indicates that the host owns the Next Descriptor in the Receive List and the DMA cannot acquire it. The Receive Process is suspended. To resume processing Receive descriptors, the host should change the ownership of the descriptor and issue a Receive Poll Demand command. If no Receive Poll Demand is issued, the Receive Process resumes when the next recognized incoming frame is received. This bit is set only when the previous Receive Descriptor is owned by the DMA.
5876 */
5877#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_MASK (0x80U)
5878#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_SHIFT (7U)
5879#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_MASK)
5880#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_RU_SHIFT)
5881
5882/*
5883 * RI (RW)
5884 *
5885 * Receive Interrupt
5886 * This bit indicates that the frame reception is complete. When reception is complete, the Bit 31 of RDES1 (Disable Interrupt on Completion) is reset in the last Descriptor, and the specific frame status information is updated in the descriptor. The reception remains in the Running state.
5887 */
5888#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_MASK (0x40U)
5889#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_SHIFT (6U)
5890#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_MASK)
5891#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_RI_SHIFT)
5892
5893/*
5894 * UNF (RW)
5895 *
5896 * Transmit Underflow
5897 * This bit indicates that the Transmit Buffer had an Underflow during frame transmission. Transmission is suspended and an Underflow Error TDES0[1] is set.
5898 */
5899#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_MASK (0x20U)
5900#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_SHIFT (5U)
5901#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_MASK)
5902#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_UNF_SHIFT)
5903
5904/*
5905 * OVF (RW)
5906 *
5907 * Receive Overflow
5908 * This bit indicates that the Receive Buffer had an Overflow during frame reception. If the partial frame is transferred to the application, the overflow status is set in RDES0[11].
5909 */
5910#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_MASK (0x10U)
5911#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_SHIFT (4U)
5912#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_MASK)
5913#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_OVF_SHIFT)
5914
5915/*
5916 * TJT (RW)
5917 *
5918 * Transmit Jabber Timeout
5919 * This bit indicates that the Transmit Jabber Timer expired, which happens when the frame size exceeds 2,048 (10,240 bytes when the Jumbo frame is enabled). When the Jabber Timeout occurs, the transmission process is aborted and placed in the Stopped state. This causes the Transmit Jabber Timeout TDES0[14] flag to assert.
5920 */
5921#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_MASK (0x8U)
5922#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_SHIFT (3U)
5923#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_MASK)
5924#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_TJT_SHIFT)
5925
5926/*
5927 * TU (RW)
5928 *
5929 * Transmit Buffer Unavailable
5930 * This bit indicates that the host owns the Next Descriptor in the Transmit List and the DMA cannot acquire it. Transmission is suspended. Bits[22:20] explain the Transmit Process state transitions. To resume processing Transmit descriptors, the host should change the ownership of the descriptor by setting TDES0[31] and then issue a Transmit Poll Demand command.
5931 */
5932#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_MASK (0x4U)
5933#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_SHIFT (2U)
5934#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_MASK)
5935#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_TU_SHIFT)
5936
5937/*
5938 * TPS (RW)
5939 *
5940 * Transmit Process Stopped
5941 * This bit is set when the transmission is stopped.
5942 */
5943#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_MASK (0x2U)
5944#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_SHIFT (1U)
5945#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_MASK)
5946#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_TPS_SHIFT)
5947
5948/*
5949 * TI (RW)
5950 *
5951 * Transmit Interrupt
5952 * This bit indicates that the frame transmission is complete. When transmission is complete, Bit 31 (OWN) of TDES0 is reset, and the specific frame status information is updated in the descriptor.
5953 */
5954#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_MASK (0x1U)
5955#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_SHIFT (0U)
5956#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_MASK)
5957#define ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_STATUS_TI_SHIFT)
5958
5959/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_OP_MODE */
5960/*
5961 * DT (RW)
5962 *
5963 * Disable Dropping of TCP/IP Checksum Error Frames
5964 * When this bit is set, the MAC does not drop the frames which only have errors detected by the Receive Checksum Offload engine. Such frames do not have any errors (including FCS error) in the Ethernet frame received by the MAC but have errors only in the encapsulated payload. When this bit is reset, all error frames are dropped if the FEF bit is reset. If the IPC Full Checksum Offload Engine (Type 2) is disabled, this bit is reserved (RO with value 1'b0).
5965 */
5966#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_MASK (0x10000000UL)
5967#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_SHIFT (28U)
5968#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_MASK)
5969#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DT_SHIFT)
5970
5971/*
5972 * RSF (RW)
5973 *
5974 * Receive Store and Forward
5975 * When this bit is set, the MTL reads a frame from the Rx FIFO only after the complete frame has been written to it, ignoring the RTC bits. When this bit is reset, the Rx FIFO operates in the cut-through mode, subject to the threshold specified by the RTC bits.
5976 */
5977#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_MASK (0x2000000UL)
5978#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_SHIFT (25U)
5979#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_MASK)
5980#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RSF_SHIFT)
5981
5982/*
5983 * DFF (RW)
5984 *
5985 * Disable Flushing of Received Frames
5986 * When this bit is set, the Rx DMA does not flush any frames because of the unavailability of receive descriptors or buffers as it does normally when this bit is reset. (See “Receive Process Suspended” on page 83.)
5987 */
5988#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_MASK (0x1000000UL)
5989#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_SHIFT (24U)
5990#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_MASK)
5991#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DFF_SHIFT)
5992
5993/*
5994 * RFA_2 (RW)
5995 *
5996 * MSB of Threshold for Activating Flow Control
5997 * If the DWC_gmac is configured for an Rx FIFO size of 8 KB or more, this bit (when set) provides additional threshold levels for activating the flow control in both half-duplex and full-duplex modes. This bit (as Most Significant Bit), along with the RFA (Bits [10:9]), gives the following thresholds for activating flow control:
5998 * - 100: Full minus 5 KB, that is, FULL — 5 KB
5999 * - 101: Full minus 6 KB, that is, FULL — 6 KB
6000 * - 110: Full minus 7 KB, that is, FULL — 7 KB
6001 * - 111: Reserved This bit is reserved (and RO) if the Rx FIFO is 4 KB or less deep.
6002 */
6003#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_MASK (0x800000UL)
6004#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_SHIFT (23U)
6005#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_MASK)
6006#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_2_SHIFT)
6007
6008/*
6009 * RFD_2 (RW)
6010 *
6011 * MSB of Threshold for Deactivating Flow Control
6012 * If the DWC_gmac is configured for Rx FIFO size of 8 KB or more, this bit (when set) provides additional threshold levels for deactivating the flow control in both half-duplex and full-duplex modes. This bit (as Most Significant Bit) along with the RFD (Bits [12:11]) gives the following thresholds for deactivating flow control:
6013 * - 100: Full minus 5 KB, that is, FULL — 5 KB
6014 * - 101: Full minus 6 KB, that is, FULL — 6 KB
6015 * - 110: Full minus 7 KB, that is, FULL — 7 KB
6016 * - 111: Reserved This bit is reserved (and RO) if the Rx FIFO is 4 KB or less deep.
6017 */
6018#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_MASK (0x400000UL)
6019#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_SHIFT (22U)
6020#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_MASK)
6021#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_2_SHIFT)
6022
6023/*
6024 * TSF (RW)
6025 *
6026 * Transmit Store and Forward
6027 * When this bit is set, transmission starts when a full frame resides in the MTL Transmit FIFO. When this bit is set, the TTC values specified in Bits [16:14] are ignored. This bit should be changed only when the transmission is stopped.
6028 */
6029#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_MASK (0x200000UL)
6030#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_SHIFT (21U)
6031#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_MASK)
6032#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TSF_SHIFT)
6033
6034/*
6035 * FTF (RW)
6036 *
6037 * Flush Transmit FIFO
6038 * When this bit is set, the transmit FIFO controller logic is reset to its default values and thus all data in the Tx FIFO is lost or flushed. This bit is cleared internally when the flushing operation is complete. The Operation Mode register should not be written to until this bit is cleared. The data which is already accepted by the MAC transmitter is not flushed. It is scheduled for transmission and results in underflow and runt frame transmission.
6039 */
6040#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_MASK (0x100000UL)
6041#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_SHIFT (20U)
6042#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_MASK)
6043#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FTF_SHIFT)
6044
6045/*
6046 * TTC (RW)
6047 *
6048 * Transmit Threshold Control
6049 * These bits control the threshold level of the MTL Transmit FIFO. Transmission starts when the frame size within the MTL Transmit FIFO is larger than the threshold. In addition, full frames with a length less than the threshold are also transmitted. These bits are used only when Bit 21 (TSF) is reset.
6050 * - 000: 64
6051 * - 001: 128
6052 * - 010: 192
6053 * - 011: 256
6054 * - 100: 40
6055 * - 101: 32
6056 * - 110: 24
6057 * - 111: 16
6058 */
6059#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_MASK (0x1C000UL)
6060#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_SHIFT (14U)
6061#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_MASK)
6062#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_TTC_SHIFT)
6063
6064/*
6065 * ST (RW)
6066 *
6067 * Start or Stop Transmission Command
6068 * When this bit is set, transmission is placed in the Running state, and the DMA checks the Transmit List at the current position for a frame to be transmitted. Descriptor acquisition is attempted either from the current position in the list, which is the Transmit List Base Address set by Register 4 (Transmit Descriptor List Address Register), or from the position retained when transmission was stopped previously. If the DMA does not own the current descriptor, transmission enters the Suspended state and Bit 2 (Transmit Buffer Unavailable) of Register 5 (Status Register) is set. The Start Transmission command is effective only when transmission is stopped. If the command is issued before setting Register 4 (Transmit Descriptor List Address Register), then the DMA behavior is unpredictable. When this bit is reset, the transmission process is placed in the Stopped state after completing the transmission of the current frame. The Next Descriptor position in the Transmit List is saved, and it becomes the current position when transmission is restarted. To change the list address, you need to program Register 4 (Transmit Descriptor List Address Register) with a new value when this bit is reset. The new value is considered when this bit is set again. The stop transmission command is effective only when the transmission of the current frame is complete or the transmission is in the Suspended state.
6069 */
6070#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_MASK (0x2000U)
6071#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_SHIFT (13U)
6072#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_MASK)
6073#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_ST_SHIFT)
6074
6075/*
6076 * RFD (RW)
6077 *
6078 * Threshold for Deactivating Flow Control (in half-duplex and full-duplex modes) These bits control the threshold (Fill-level of Rx FIFO) at which the flow control is de-asserted after activation.
6079 * - 00: Full minus 1 KB, that is, FULL — 1 KB
6080 * - 01: Full minus 2 KB, that is, FULL — 2 KB
6081 * - 10: Full minus 3 KB, that is, FULL — 3 KB
6082 * - 11: Full minus 4 KB, that is, FULL — 4 KB The de-assertion is effective only after flow control is asserted. If the Rx FIFO is 8 KB or more, an additional Bit (RFD_2) is used for more threshold levels as described in Bit 22. These bits are reserved and read-only when the Rx FIFO depth is less than 4 KB.
6083 */
6084#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_MASK (0x1800U)
6085#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_SHIFT (11U)
6086#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_MASK)
6087#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFD_SHIFT)
6088
6089/*
6090 * RFA (RW)
6091 *
6092 * Threshold for Activating Flow Control (in half-duplex and full-duplex modes) These bits control the threshold (Fill level of Rx FIFO) at which the flow control is activated.
6093 * - 00: Full minus 1 KB, that is, FULL—1KB.
6094 * - 01: Full minus 2 KB, that is, FULL—2KB.
6095 * - 10: Full minus 3 KB, that is, FULL—3KB.
6096 * - 11: Full minus 4 KB, that is, FULL—4KB. These values are applicable only to Rx FIFOs of 4 KB or more and when Bit 8 (EFC) is set high. If the Rx FIFO is 8 KB or more, an additional Bit (RFA_2) is used for more threshold levels as described in Bit 23. These bits are reserved and read-only when the depth of Rx FIFO is less than 4 KB. Note: When FIFO size is exactly 4 KB, although the DWC_gmac allows you to program the value of these bits to 11, the software should not program these bits to 2'b11. The value 2'b11 means flow control on FIFO empty condition
6097 */
6098#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_MASK (0x600U)
6099#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_SHIFT (9U)
6100#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_MASK)
6101#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RFA_SHIFT)
6102
6103/*
6104 * EFC (RW)
6105 *
6106 * Enable HW Flow Control
6107 * When this bit is set, the flow control signal operation based on the fill-level of Rx FIFO is enabled. When reset, the flow control operation is disabled. This bit is not used (reserved and always reset) when the Rx FIFO is less than 4 KB.
6108 */
6109#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_MASK (0x100U)
6110#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_SHIFT (8U)
6111#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_MASK)
6112#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_EFC_SHIFT)
6113
6114/*
6115 * FEF (RW)
6116 *
6117 * Forward Error Frames
6118 * When this bit is reset, the Rx FIFO drops frames with error status (CRC error, collision error, GMII_ER, giant frame, watchdog timeout, or overflow). However, if the start byte (write) pointer of a frame is already transferred to the read controller side (in Threshold mode), then the frame is not dropped. In the GMAC-MTL configuration in which the Frame Length FIFO is also enabled during core configuration, the Rx FIFO drops the error frames if that frame's start byte is not transferred (output) on the ARI bus. When the FEF bit is set, all frames except runt error frames are forwarded to the DMA. If the Bit 25 (RSF) is set and the Rx FIFO overflows when a partial frame is written, then the frame is dropped irrespective of the FEF bit setting. However, if the Bit 25 (RSF) is reset and the Rx FIFO overflows when a partial frame is written, then a partial frame may be forwarded to the DMA. Note: When FEF bit is reset, the giant frames are dropped if the giant frame status is given in Rx Status (in Table 8-6 or Table 8-23) in the following configurations: - The IP checksum engine (Type 1) and full checksum offload engine (Type 2) are not selected. - The advanced timestamp feature is not selected but the extended status is selected. The extended status is available with the following features: - L3-L4 filter in GMAC-CORE or GMAC-MTL configurations - Full checksum offload engine (Type 2) with enhanced descriptor format in the GMAC-DMA, GMAC-AHB, or GMAC-AXI configurations.
6119 */
6120#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_MASK (0x80U)
6121#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_SHIFT (7U)
6122#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_MASK)
6123#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FEF_SHIFT)
6124
6125/*
6126 * FUF (RW)
6127 *
6128 * Forward Undersized Good Frames
6129 * When set, the Rx FIFO forwards Undersized frames (that is, frames with no Error and length less than 64 bytes) including pad-bytes and CRC. When reset, the Rx FIFO drops all frames of less than 64 bytes, unless a frame is already transferred because of the lower value of Receive Threshold, for example, RTC = 01.
6130 */
6131#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_MASK (0x40U)
6132#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_SHIFT (6U)
6133#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_MASK)
6134#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_FUF_SHIFT)
6135
6136/*
6137 * DGF (RW)
6138 *
6139 * Drop Giant Frames
6140 * When set, the MAC drops the received giant frames in the Rx FIFO, that is, frames that are larger than the computed giant frame limit. When reset, the MAC does not drop the giant frames in the Rx FIFO. Note: This bit is available in the following configurations in which the giant frame status is not provided in Rx status and giant frames are not dropped by default: - Configurations in which IP Checksum Offload (Type 1) is selected in Rx - Configurations in which the IPC Full Checksum Offload Engine (Type 2) is selected in Rx with normal descriptor format - Configurations in which the Advanced Timestamp feature is selected In all other configurations, this bit is not used (reserved and always reset).
6141 */
6142#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_MASK (0x20U)
6143#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_SHIFT (5U)
6144#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_MASK)
6145#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_DGF_SHIFT)
6146
6147/*
6148 * RTC (RW)
6149 *
6150 * Receive Threshold Control
6151 * These two bits control the threshold level of the MTL Receive FIFO. Transfer (request) to DMA starts when the frame size within the MTL Receive FIFO is larger than the threshold. In addition, full frames with length less than the threshold are automatically transferred. The value of 11 is not applicable if the configured Receive FIFO size is 128 bytes. These bits are valid only when the RSF bit is zero, and are ignored when the RSF bit is set to 1.
6152 * - 00: 64
6153 * - 01: 32
6154 * - 10: 96
6155 * - 11: 128
6156 */
6157#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_MASK (0x18U)
6158#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_SHIFT (3U)
6159#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_MASK)
6160#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_RTC_SHIFT)
6161
6162/*
6163 * OSF (RW)
6164 *
6165 * Operate on Second Frame
6166 * When this bit is set, it instructs the DMA to process the second frame of the Transmit data even before the status for the first frame is obtained.
6167 */
6168#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_MASK (0x4U)
6169#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_SHIFT (2U)
6170#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_MASK)
6171#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_OSF_SHIFT)
6172
6173/*
6174 * SR (RW)
6175 *
6176 * Start or Stop Receive
6177 * When this bit is set, the Receive process is placed in the Running state. The DMA attempts to acquire the descriptor from the Receive list and processes the incoming frames. The descriptor acquisition is attempted from the current position in the list, which is the address set by the Register 3 (Receive Descriptor List Address Register) or the position retained when the Receive process was previously stopped. If the DMA does not own the descriptor, reception is suspended and Bit 7 (Receive Buffer Unavailable) of Register 5 (Status Register) is set. The Start Receive command is effective only when the reception has stopped. If the command is issued before setting Register 3 (Receive Descriptor List Address Register), the DMA behavior is unpredictable. When this bit is cleared, the Rx DMA operation is stopped after the transfer of the current frame. The next descriptor position in the Receive list is saved and becomes the current position after the Receive process is restarted. The Stop Receive command is effective only when the Receive process is in either the Running (waiting for receive packet) or in the Suspended state.
6178 */
6179#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_MASK (0x2U)
6180#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_SHIFT (1U)
6181#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_MASK)
6182#define ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_OP_MODE_SR_SHIFT)
6183
6184/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_INTR_EN */
6185/*
6186 * NIE (RW)
6187 *
6188 * Normal Interrupt Summary Enable
6189 * When this bit is set, normal interrupt summary is enabled. When this bit is reset, normal interrupt summary is disabled. This bit enables the following interrupts in Register 5 (Status Register): - Register 5[0]: Transmit Interrupt - Register 5[2]: Transmit Buffer Unavailable - Register 5[6]: Receive Interrupt - Register 5[14]: Early Receive Interrupt
6190 */

6195

6197 * AIE (RW)
6198 *
6199 * Abnormal Interrupt Summary Enable
6200 * When this bit is set, abnormal interrupt summary is enabled. When this bit is reset, the abnormal interrupt summary is disabled. This bit enables the following interrupts in Register 5 (Status Register): - Register 5[1]: Transmit Process Stopped - Register 5[3]: Transmit Jabber Timeout - Register 5[4]: Receive Overflow - Register 5[5]: Transmit Underflow - Register 5[7]: Receive Buffer Unavailable - Register 5[8]: Receive Process Stopped - Register 5[9]: Receive Watchdog Timeout - Register 5[10]: Early Transmit Interrupt - Register 5[13]: Fatal Bus Error

6350/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT */
6351/*
6352 * ONFCNTOVF (RW)
6353 *
6354 * Overflow Bit for FIFO Overflow Counter
6355 * This bit is set every time the Overflow Frame Counter (Bits[27:17]) overflows, that is, the Rx FIFO overflows with the overflow frame counter at maximum value. In such a scenario, the overflow frame counter is reset to all-zeros and this bit indicates that the rollover happened.
6356 */
6357#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_MASK (0x10000000UL)
6358#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_SHIFT (28U)
6359#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_MASK)
6360#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_ONFCNTOVF_SHIFT)
6361
6362/*
6363 * OVFFRMCNT (RW)
6364 *
6365 * Overflow Frame Counter
6366 * This field indicates the number of frames missed by the application. This counter is incremented each time the MTL FIFO overflows. The counter is cleared when this register is read with mci_be_i[2] at 1’b1.
6367 */
6368#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_MASK (0xFFE0000UL)
6369#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_SHIFT (17U)
6370#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_MASK)
6371#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_OVFFRMCNT_SHIFT)
6372
6373/*
6374 * MISCNTOVF (RW)
6375 *
6376 * Overflow Bit for Missed Frame Counter
6377 * This bit is set every time Missed Frame Counter (Bits[15:0]) overflows, that is, the DMA discards an incoming frame because of the Host Receive Buffer being unavailable with the missed frame counter at maximum value. In such a scenario, the Missed frame counter is reset to all-zeros and this bit indicates that the rollover happened.
6378 */
6379#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_MASK (0x10000UL)
6380#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_SHIFT (16U)
6381#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_MASK)
6382#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISCNTOVF_SHIFT)
6383
6384/*
6385 * MISFRMCNT (RW)
6386 *
6387 * Missed Frame Counter
6388 * This field indicates the number of frames missed by the controller because of the Host Receive Buffer being unavailable. This counter is incremented each time the DMA discards an incoming frame. The counter is cleared when this register is read with mci_be_i[0] at 1’b1.
6389 */
6390#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISFRMCNT_MASK (0xFFFFU)
6391#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISFRMCNT_SHIFT (0U)
6392#define ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISFRMCNT_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISFRMCNT_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_MISS_OVF_CNT_MISFRMCNT_MASK)

6395/* Bitfield definition for register: DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG */
6396/*
6397 * RIWT (RW)
6398 *
6399 * RI Watchdog Timer Count
6400 * This bit indicates the number of system clock cycles multiplied by 256 for which the watchdog timer is set. The watchdog timer gets triggered with the programmed value after the Rx DMA completes the transfer of a frame for which the RI status bit is not set because of the setting in the corresponding descriptor RDES1[31]. When the watchdog timer runs out, the RI bit is set and the timer is stopped. The watchdog timer is reset when the RI bit is set high because of automatic setting of RI as per RDES1[31] of any received frame.
6401 */
6402#define ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_MASK (0xFFU)
6403#define ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_SHIFT (0U)
6404#define ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_SET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) << ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_SHIFT) & ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_MASK)
6405#define ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_GET(x) (((uint32_t)(x) & ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_MASK) >> ENET_DMA_RX_INTR_WDOG_RIWT_SHIFT)
6406

6409 * EN_LPI (RW)

6552 * UNDEF (RW)
6553 *
6554 * AXI Undefined Burst Length
6555 * This bit is read-only bit and indicates the complement (invert) value of Bit 16 (FB) in Register 0 (Bus Mode Register). - When this bit is set to 1, the GMAC-AXI is allowed to perform any burst length equal to or below the maximum allowed burst length programmed in Bits[7:3]. - When this bit is set to 0, the GMAC-AXI is allowed to perform only fixed burst lengths as indicated by BLEN256, BLEN128, BLEN64, BLEN32, BLEN16, BLEN8, or BLEN4, or a burst length of 1. If UNDEF is set and none of the BLEN bits is set, then GMAC-AXI is allowed to perform a burst length of 16.
6556 */

6635 * ACTPHYIF (RW)

6637 * Active or selected PHY interface
6638 * When you have multiple PHY interfaces in your configuration, this field indicates the sampled value of phy_intf_sel_i during reset de-assertion.

6642 * - 011: TBI
